english:
  title: On Why the Tang History Failed to Establish a Separate Biography for Choe Chi-won
  author: Lee Kyubo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Examining the Bibliographic Section of the Tang History, I find that Choe Chi-won's parallel prose essays comprise one volume, and his Cassia Garden's Writing Labor fills twenty more. The annotation notes: "A man of Koryo who achieved the civil service examination through tributary recommendation, becoming an official under Gao Bian in Huainan." Reading this, I cannot but admire the magnanimous spirit of the Chinese. They did not diminish a foreigner's worth, yet published his collected works for posterity and recorded them thus in their histories.

    Yet I confess puzzlement: why did they not compose a separate biography for Chi-won in the section devoted to literary masters? If one claims his deeds insufficient for biography, consider this: the Lonely Cloud—as Choe Chi-won was known—crossed the sea at twelve to study in the Middle Kingdom. He passed the examinations on his first attempt, became an official under Gao Bian, and sent dispatches that so demoralized the rebel Huang Chao that his spirit wavered. Chi-won rose to the rank of Grand Inspector. When departing to return home, his examination-mate Gu Yun presented him with the Song of the Sage-Scholar, which sang: "At twelve he sailed across the sea; his writings stirred the heart of China." Such evident accomplishments would certainly warrant a biography surpassing the half-page accounts given to men like Shen Quanqi, Liu Bing, Cui Yuanhan, and Li Pin in those same literary records.

    If their excuse is that foreigners already appear in the bibliographic section, consider this: in the records of military commanders, Li Zhengji and Heichi Changzhi—both Koryo men—each received full biographies detailing their deeds. Why then does the literary section alone deny Chi-won his due recognition? I venture a private conjecture: the ancients harbored professional jealousy in matters of letters. When a foreign youth entered their court and surpassed their celebrated scholars, such excellence bred resentment. Perhaps they feared that recording his true merit would expose this shame. Yet I remain uncertain of their reasoning.
  footnotes:
    - Choe Chi-won (846-910), known as the Lonely Cloud (孤雲), was a Silla scholar-official who achieved remarkable success in Tang China before returning to Korea.
    - The 'parallel prose essays' (四六文) refer to a sophisticated literary form popular in medieval China, requiring matched couplets of four and six characters.
    - Lee Kyubo (1168-1241) was a Koryo literatus and historian writing this critique centuries after Chi-won's era, reflecting on the Tang History's treatment of this accomplished Korean figure.
